      <title>Chinese jaywalkers cross six-lane road by squeezing through crack</title>
      <description><![CDATA[XINING, CHINA <br/> Why did the pedestrians cross the road? So they could use a tiny hole in the middle of a median barrier that wasn't meant for people. <br/>Pedestrians from the city of Xining located in fabulous Qinghai province have found themselves between a concrete median and some metal fencing. <br/>According to Pear Video, people having to hoof it along a massively long, six-lane street with few crosswalks have been forced to take matters into their own hands. <br/>People have been forced to squeeze themselves through a tiny opening in the middle of the busy street because walking down to actual crosswalks could take as long as 20 minutes, according to one person interviewed by Pear Video. <br/>The tiny crack definitely saves people a lot of time, but it also depends on how low you can go.  <br/>And then there's the whole risking your life trying to get across the road part that people also need to deal with. <br/>Either way, this is a clear cut example of some top notch civil engineering.]]></description>
